In general, the dielectric constant of LCs decreases at high temperatures and increases at low temperatures. This is due to the fact that the orientation of liquid crystal molecules is affected by temperature, and the arrangement of them are more disordered at high temperatures, which causes the intermolecular interactions to change, thus affecting the dielectric properties of LC. In addition, the loss factor (\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
